The paper proposes an extension to Value Iteration Networks (VINs) for robot motion planning, which is a topic that falls under the intersection of several computer science subfields. Based on the content of the abstract, the most likely sub-category is cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), as the paper discusses learning-based methods for planning robot motion. The second most likely sub-category is cs.RO (Robotics), as the paper specifically addresses the applicability of VINs to real-world planning problems. The third most likely sub-category is cs.LG (Machine Learning), as VINs are a type of neural network architecture. The fourth most likely sub-category is cs.CV (Computer Vision), as the paper discusses the representation of the robot's vicinity. The fifth most likely sub-category is cs.SY (Systems and Control), as the paper discusses the planning of omnidirectional driving for a search-and-rescue robot.
